{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930101801/0055.xml":{"full_text":"Financial Market News, Stocks, Bonds, Commodities and Comment\n[W HILLY IS PREDICTED'\nI BY THE SPECTATOR\ndecline of 9.25 Points in Averages and Huge\nShort Sales Leave Opening For Technical\nRise; Caution Is Advised\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nIn view of the break of 9.25 points in the averages yester\nday, I wouldn\u2019t be a bit surprised to see further weakness at\nthe opening today. Over-night accumulation of selling orders\nand the liquidation of some under-margined accounts ought\n.'to accomplish this.\nActivity Increased somewhat on the decline which might\nbe taken as an indication that the bears have shaken off\nfears that they would find it hard to borrow stock to\ncover their contracts. I think there was more short selling\nyesterday than at'any time this week, and if there was, then\nthe market ought to be able to rally more easily, once\ncovering operations are begun.\nBecause of this, I think the market can be bought for a\n\u201cturn.\u201d But bear this in mind, you\u2019ve got to watch the\ntape and get out -as soon as you\u2019ve got a fair-sized profit.\nI don\u2019t say you\u2019ll get your profit today, but I am of the\nopinion that either in the last half hour today or during\nthe early part of Monday\u2019s session you\u2019ll be able to realise\na fair-sized profit on stocks picked up during the first\nhours today.\nHf Allegheny\nAlthough there is still the pos-\nF slbility that the stock will react\ntwo or three points more, I think\nAllegheny has dropped to the\npoint where it can be bought\nand held for a fair-sized profit,\np While the company\u2019s earnings\nthis year are materially below\nthose of 1929, its sponsorship is\nof the best in the street, and a\nthree or four point recovery in\nthe stock wouldn\u2019t surprise me a\nbit. I don\u2019t forget that three or\nfour points in a stock of this\npr|ce is a good profit.\nEstimated earnings of approxi-\nmately 80 cents a share on Union\nCarbide\u2019s capital stock only bears\nout what I \u2019said in this column\nbefore, viz: That the third and\nlast quarters of the year are Car\nbide\u2019s best periods, and the com\npany should at least cover its\ndividend requirements of $2.60 a\nshare.\nGillette\nGillette slid off more than five\npoints in yesterday\u2019s reaction.\nThis is only natural, as the\nstock is still vulnerable to bear\nattacks. As I pointed out yes-\nI terday, the stock will probably\nkr. continue to decline with the gen\np oral list, but in view of the fact\nthat as 4 dividend rate is assured.\nfor a while at least. I think\nI Gillette is a good long-pull propo\nsition. I\u2019d hold onto any stock\nI had and buy on further price\nrecessions.\n\nChanging the tffcme of the\nPrince Whitely Trading Cor\njioration won\u2019t help much as far\nVis I can see.\nLoew\u2019s\nBreaking more than five points,\nLoew\u2019s got down to around the\nlow point of the current reaction\nat $54. If everything in the com\npany is as good as it is said to\nbe. and I can see no reason for\nk believing that it isn\u2019t, then Loew's\nk is selling away out of line. I\nk rill think Loew\u2019s is one of the\nK' test issues on the board, and\nH .hile it may show some further\nMl softness, I think the minor re-\nMotions can be disregarded and\nI the stock held for good profits on\nne pull.\nThe placing of several large\nF SUNK ASKS SUIT\nDISMISSAL\nThe Merchants Bank and Trust\nCompany yesterday moved to ob-\ntain dismissal of the suit filed\nearlier in the week by Joseph W.\nMc\u00dfeynolds to halt the merger of\nthe bank with the Federal Ameri\ncan National Bank until his claim\nfor the return of a note for\n$50,000 and a 'large money judg\n-4 -tent could be heard. Mc\u00dfeynolds\nR. laimed that he had been deceived\nHo n a real estate transaction by\nPeter A. Drury, chairman of the\nV ooard of directors of the bank.\nAttorneys Ellis, Ferguson and\nF Gary filed the motion to dismiss,\nsaying that there is no occasion to\nBa halt the proposed merger because\nunder its terms the Federal-Ameri\ncan National Bank assumes all\nthe liabilities of the other bank\nand Mc\u00dfeynolds can enforce his\nrights, if he has any, against the\nmerged institution as easily as he\ncould against the other.\njit is also contended that Mc-\nReynold* cannot enjoin the nego\ntlation of the notes because they\nare overdue and he has not\ntendered payment.\nUtility Firm Faces\n$12,500,000 Suits\nMONTICELLO. N. Y., Oct 1 18\n(tjfJS.).\u2014Two suits totaling sl2,-\n500,000 against the Rockland\nLight and Power Company were\nfiled in Supreme Court here by\nb Capt. Delfungo Gierea. minority\nstockholder of the company.\nCaptain Gierea charged that the\ncompany \u201cwatered its stock to the\nextent of $12.000,000.-\nrail orders by the carriers only\nbears out what Iron Age sai-1 on\nWednesday, that the rail orders\nwere the bright spot of the week\nin the steel industry. But neither\nthe-steel nor the rail business are\nin the best of health right now,\nalthough some improvement can\nbe expected.\nNew Haven\nWhile on the subject of the\nrails. New Haven continues to\nmystify the trading fraternity.\nIn |the Iface of the President\u2019s\nstatement that the road would\ncontinue the $6 dividend rate in\n1931 the stock slumped three\npoints to a new low for the year.\nAt its current levels. New Haven\nis yielding close to 6.60 per cent\nwhich, in view of Mr. Pelley\u2019s\nannouncement, is a substantial\nreturn and should attract some\nInvestment buying.\nThe visit of Bernard M. Baruch\nto President Hoover stirred up\nconsiderable attention in the\nstreet and was rather perplexing.\nNo one seemed to know what it\nwas all about. And for that mat\nter, neither do I.\nHere and There\nMost of market commentators\nwent a bit askew on their predic\ntions. J. F. Hughes, who inci\ndentally has been right on the\nmarket says that the relative lack\nof technical strength in the lead\ning stocks leads to questioning\nthe ability of the market gen\nerally to accomplish a full tech\nnical recovery of half the ground\nJost since September 10. And we\nagree with him.\nFavorable statements regarding\nearnings has led to some scat\ntered buying of First National\nStores. In this group, however, I\nthink one should watch one\u2019s\nstep.\nSome of the department store\nstocks, such as Best and Com\npany and R. H. Macy, appeared\nto be reasonably priced. At least\nthey ought to be amonk the first\nto reflect an upswing in the\ngroup.\nMany seem to think that a real\nrecovery can\u2019t set in until the\nrails have had a fair-sized reac\ntion. If what the carriers have\nbeen doing up to now isn\u2019t re\naction then the Pennsylvania is\nnothing but a shuttle line.\nBROKERS SEE\nDULL MART\nStocks selling on an attractive\ninvestment yield basis are attrac\ntive on reaction.\u2014M. J. MEE\nHAN CO.\nMarket we saw early will be\nfamiliar for some weeks to come.\nIt\u2019is the period of dullness which\nfollows a drastic break in the\nmarket.\u2014BAA\u00df, COHEN Co.\nLook for an irregular market.\u2014\nTOBEY KIRK.\nTrading today will be faced\nwith some pressure.\u2014HORN\nBLOWER WEEKS.\nBe prepared to take on mod\nerate trading lines on reactions.\n-EMANUEL <fc CO.\nDo not feel justified in sugges\ning short term trading commit\nments.\u2014OTlS CO.\nw. B. HIBBS CO.\nTile ONLY \u2018New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nMEMBERS\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\n1 Philadelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nAdvisor\n1I\n\u25a0r\n\u25a0km\nE 1* \u2019>J\nkJ\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nEUGENE BLACK\nGOVERNOR OF the Federal\nReserve Bank of Atlanta, who\nat a recent meeting of the\nInvestment Bankers of America\ndeclared that it was necessary\nthat the public \u201cpay debts and\ngo to work\u201d in order to Insure\nthe return of prosperity.\nPRICESREMAIN\nSTEADY\nThe general level of wholesale\nprices in September varied little\nfrom the August level, the Bureau\nof Labor Statistics announced to\nday, placing the purchasing\npower of the 1926 dollar in that\nmonth at SI.BB.\nPrices of farm products showed\nan average gain of of 1 per\ncent, large decreases in grains\nand cotton being more than off\nset by increases in beef steers,\nhogs, poultry, eggs, and potatoes.\nFoods, as a whole, rose ap\npreciably, the net increase being\nnearly P er cent. Among\narticles increasing in price were\nbutter, cheese, fresh beef and\npork, bacon, coffee, canned beans\nand corn, fish, and oranges.\nWheat and rye flour, on the other\nhand, averaged lower than in\nAugust. Hides and skins ad\nvanced in price, while leather de\nclined, and boots and shoes and\nother leather products were prac\ntically stationary.\nTextile products showed a per\nceptible decrease, cotton goods,\nsilk and rayon, woolen and\nworsted goods and other textile\nproducts sharing in the decline.\nFuel and lighting materials\nmoved upward, anthracite and\nbituminous coal, coke, and pe\ntroleum products being at higher\nlevels than in August.\nMetal products, as a whole,\nmoved downward, iron and steel\nand nonferrous metals contribut\ning to the lower prices.\nReceiver Is Asked\nFor Mortgage Firm\nALEXANDRIA, Va\u201e Oct. 18\nThe petition filed by a committee\nof stockholders asking' appoint\nment of a receiver for the Ward\nman Mortgage and Discount Cor\nporation, of Washington, and is\nsuance of an injunction to pre\nvent an advertised meeting of\nthe. stockholders here Monday for\nthe purpose of dissolving the cor\nporation, Was taken under advise\nment by Corporation Judge Wil\nliam P. Woolls following a three\nhour argument of the petition to\nday. He announced a decision\nwould be handed down before\nMonday.\nIndustrial Activity\nLow in September\nNot only has industrial produc\ntion. viewed in the aggregate,\nfailed to expand sharply during\nrecent weeks, but preliminary\ndata indicate that after correc\ntion for seasonal variation, Sep\ntember output reached a new bot\ntom on the decline which has\nbeen in progress since May, 1929.\nAs preliminarily computed, the\nStandard Statistics Company\ncomposite index stood at 97.6 last\nmonth, as compared with the\nfinal figure of 99.1 for August,\nand 129.9 for September, 1929.\nBusiness Should Continue\nSpHirtff F.ffnrts\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nDirector New York University Bnresn\nof Business Research and Former\nKconnmist of Federal Trade\nCommission\nThe two great needs in business\ntoday are (1) a steady effort to\nsell goods, and (2) an intelligent\neffort to get in shape to make\nsales.\nBy the former, I mean that\nbusiness men should continue to\nuse every sound effort to urge\nconsumers to buy. While cutting\nout the wasteful frills and doubt\nful experiments, they should keep\nup advertising in proven media.\nThey should keep on their best\nsalesmen.\nThey should build for the fu\nture. By doing so, they will help\nto change the unduly pessimistic\nattitude of many consumers.\nBy the second point, I mean\nthat business men should direct\ntheir selling efforts with due rec\nognition of the existing situation.\nIt is foolish to try to keep prices\nout of line with the general level.\nThe general spirit is one of eco\nnomy. To try to buck this spirit\n(which is a sound and logical\none) by appeals to buy things\nmerely because they are luxuries,\nwill be of little avail.\nStandard Goods Best\nThe emphasis should be put\nupon standard goods. The prac\ntical importance or usefulness or\neven necessity of the product\nshould be emphasized. And prices\nshould be made right. This may\ninclude the adoption of economics\nin production, in order to make\nlower prices possible and profit\nable.\nThe best way to overcome any\nunwarranted pessimism is to get\nbusy. The psychology of trying\nCOPPER TRADE\nSHOWS DROP\nSales of copper fell off sharply\nin the last week, contrasted with\nthe large volume booked in the\ntwo preceding weeks, but this oc\ncasioned no great surprise, and\nproducers maintained the 10-cent\nprice, delivered Connecticut, re\nports Metal and Mineral Markets.\nLower prices obtained during the\nweek on lead, zinc and tin.\nSeptember statistics revealed\nanother substantial increase in\nstocks of refined copper, which\nhad the effect of reviving talk of\nanother drastic cut in output. Re\nports on the movement of copper\ninto consuming channels are being\nscanned carefully, and so tar they\nfail to show that any substantial\nimprovement has set in, not\nwithstanding recent price reduc\ntions. Only the electrical indus\ntry seems to have taken advantage\nof the present situation in copper.\nExport business for the week was\nfair, bringing the total sales for\nthe first half of October to 24,500\nlong tons.\nB. O. to Spend\n4 Million on Cars\nDirectors of the Baltimore and\nOhio Railroad have authorized\nthe expenditure of $4,000,000 in\na car-building program. The plan\ncalls for the construction of 2,000\nsteel cars, one half box cars and\none half gondola coal cars. It\nwill provide between 60,000 and\n70,000 days of work.\nThe Baltimore and Ohio has\nno immediate need for the 2,000\ncars at the present time, but the\nmanagement was prompted to\nauthorize the construction by a\ndesire to provide employment for\nmen whose work might otherwise\nnot be required.\nAT YOUR THEATER TONIGHT I\nOFFICIAL PROGRAMS of Theater Member, of the\nMotion Picture Theater Owner, of District of Columbia\nWARNER BROS. THEATERS\nAMBASSADOR EARLE TBSrfJW\n___ _ \"Indian. Ara Coming,\" No. 1 On th. Staje\u2014Nick Lucas in Person\nPALACE\u2014F St at 13tti\nAPOLLO 5T* HOME u \u00a3\u00ab8,25\"\nO Stage\u2014\"ROT AL REVELS\u201d T\nBen Blue, Master of Ceremonies OLB E N and JOHNSON EDDIE FO T, JR..\nF HEARST METROTONE NEWS in \"OH. SAILOR. BEHAVE\u201d in \"LEATHERNECKING\nPALACE ORCHESTRA Comedy and Vitaphone Variety Comedy\nCOLUMBIA\u2014FSt at 12th IVAION Connecticut Ave. and METDOPOI ITAN\n_ Grace Moore, the Great American RwfiLUR McKinley St. D. C. Mll lIUI ULII RH at Tenth\nI Soprano, in \"A Lady\u2019s Morals.\u201d JOHN GARRTcw i> '.tixs. TACK HOLT\nsnd TH Sertah T in \"THE SQUEALER\u201d\nBeery. Venal Added Offering. \"Indians Ar. Comin.,\u201d No. 2 Added Short Subjects\nOVATE Bethesda, 11\nAVENUE GRAND I\u2019/\u201d- SAVOY \u2022ML-Sf\nWaters.\u201d and \"Cameo Kirby\u201d _ rex LEASE In \"WINGS OF AD- GEORGE O\u2019BRIEN\nDEBIIDI If* Phone North ISM V \u00ae?,L? RB c \u00b0\u2122edy and Serial, ,n\nKCrUBLIU V St- Near 14th. Indians Are Comin.,\u201d No. 1 Comedy\nWARNER BAXTER\nin \"Romance of the Rio Grande\u201d OFNTRAI Ninth St. Between TIVM I 14th and Park Road\nI I IMPfll M 18,8 U Bt N w wEHIIWL D and E Btl I I YULI Northwest\nLINUULH DOUGLAS FAIRBANKS. JR., and OLSEN A JOHNSON in \u2018OH. SAILOR.\nJohn Barrymore In \u201cMobey Dick\u201d BILLIE DOVE in \u201cONE NIGHT BEHAVE.\u2019 Comedy and Serial\u2014\nwith a Splendid Cast AT SUSIE\u2019S.\u201d Comedy \u201cIndians Are Cominy. No. 2\nH BOOKER T 143 (TalWe) N W COLONY Geetkla Avenue and VfIDK Georgia Avenue and\nKay Johnaon-Reainald Denny UULURI Farraaut St. lURR Quebec Street\nT \"MADAM SATAN\u201d WILL ROGERS JOE COOK\nMRAAII 11 lift FSt S W OR SHINE\u201d\nROSALIA IS 18 LONDON Sportlirht Reel\nW g d TAKOMA F^ r,h Dd Butternut. ft Wft KEITHS 15 th\nN BBflinWlV ,S 7th Bt N W Takoma Park. D. C. K\u201cA\"U ftEI IHO Sta. N. W.\na OnUMUWIIT (Near PJ Talktar Pictures at Their Beet BERT LTTELL tn \"BROTHERS\u201d\n8 CLARENCE BROOKS In REX LEAIE in \"TROOPERS THREE.\u201d with Dorethy Sebastian and a Splen-\n-GEORGIA ROSE\" and \u201cLAND OF MISSING MEN\u201d did Supporttaf Cast. Added Features\nThe National Daily\nto do something is essentially a\nhopeful psychology. This not\nonly bucks the seller up, but it\ngets across to the buyer the fact\nthat business is going on and\nthat there is a future.\nBy all this I am far from mean\ning the hysterical appeals. These\nare obviously cries for help! The\npsychology of please to \u201cbuy a\nbale,\u201d etc., is bad. Consumers do\nnot react to requests to help the\npoor business man.\nA Futile Ballyhoo\nSuch ballyhoo is always futile.\nFirst, it is based on unsound prin\nciples. Saving, not spending,\nmakes business good, because we\nhave to save in order to spend.\nSecoild, even if they were ef\nfective, such pleas for indlscrimi\nnative buying could only produce\na temporary spurt.\nThird, they can\u2019t be effective\nbecause many incomes are tem\nporarily reduced and economy is\nnecessary.\nWe should remember that econ\nomy and thrift do not mean ab\nsence of business or of buying. If\nwe were always thrifty and eco\nnomical, business would always\nbe good\u2014not \u201cbooming,\u201d but\ngood.\nAt present things are wearing\nout or getting obsolete. Consum\ners\u2019 reserve supplies are gradually\nbeing exhausted. Moreover, the\nnovelty of the impulse to econo\nmize is wearing off. At the same\ntime people are saving and re\ncuperating.\nIn time these developments will\nboth stimulate Increased buying\nand also make it possible. By\nkeeping up their selling efforts on\nsound lines, business\u00abmen can\nhasten this time. Those who do\nso will be on the train when it\nstarts.\nSELF SUPPORT\nIS SEEN\nUnited States is In a better\nposition to become self-sufficient\nif nationalistic policies rule the\nworld over than any other coun\ntry, according to J. H. Lewis, of\nGoodbody Co., who points out\nthat we consume over 90 per\ncent of the commodities we pro\nduce and that with normal con\nsumption in this country and our\npresent reduced rate of foreign\ntrade a 97 per cent of normal\nbusiness volume could be expected.\nMr. Lewis declared:\n\u201cBut before this country can\nstart on another period of\nprosperity it seems that certain\nfinal economic adjustments\nmust be made. Our large cor\nporations are geared to a super\nnormal domestic demand plus\nnormal and expanding foreign\nsales. On such a basis high\nwages are in order. But now,\nwith consumption both here and\nabroad under normal, corpor\nate profits are melting. Such\nconditions result in the post\nponement of capital expenditure\nprograms. Corporate profits\nare a source of mass confi\ndence. When the earning\npower of our hosts of corpora\ntions is on the upgrade con\nstructive efforts are unleashed\nin every direction and a feeling\nof confidence prevails.\n\u201cHowever, a logical precedent\nto a reduction in the labor\ncosts of corporations is a de\ncrease in the cost of living.\nJust that has been happening\nin the past year.\u201d\nWIN A PRIZE! Detailed in\nformation on the $125 PRIZE\nCONTEST now in progress ap\npears on next to last page of\nthir paper.\nSATURDAY\u2014OCTOBER 18\u20141930\nENGINEERS RAP\nENTHUSIASTIC\nPESSIMISTS\nBusiness and Trade Experts\nHit Attitude That Commerce\nIs on the Rocks Now\nThe sightseeing trip of .busk\nness into the vale of despond\nwas cited as the cause of the\neconomic depression which the\nUnited States now finds itself\nin by the Society of Industrial\nEngineers in convention here.\nResolutions adopted by the en\ngineers sized up the economic\nsituation in this manner:\n\u201cEnthusiastic pessimism is\nraising hell with business in\nthe United States today.\n\"There is no excuse for con\ntinuation of the present sight\nseeing trip of business into the\nvale of despond. Fundamental\neconomic conditions are sound.\nOptimism, courageous use of\ncredit and increased spending\nare the ingredients for a gen\nerous dose of common sense\nneeded by the victims of pessi\nmistic whooping cough.\u201d\nThe organization is made up\nof business engineers who are\nconcerned with the management\nproblems of machines and men\nin industry.\nAnother portion \u00bbof the resolu\ntion adopted by the engineers\nwas:\n\u201cThe key log of the jam is\nunemployment. Give the work\ners work to do and they will\nbuy.\u201d\nThe statement of the society,\nclosely connected as it is witn\nbusiness generally caused consid\nerable comment in industrial and\ncommercial circles. It is thought\nthat this is the first time such\na definite statement has been\nmade by any one business group.\nBudd Manufacturing\nOmits Its Dividend\nDirectors of the Edward O.\nBudd Manufacturing Company\nomitted the regular quarterly\ndividend. The regular preferred\ndividend of 1% per cent on the\n7 per preferred stock was\ndeclared to holders of record\nOctober 27, payable November 1.\nWhile the present reduced busi\nness shows some earnings, these\nearnings were not sufficient to\nmeet the common dividend. The\ncompany has a large volume of\norders on its books, which will\nrequire substantial cash outlays\nupon the revival of business.\nWall Street\nHears:\nThat National Dairy (NPT)\nwill net about $4 a share this\nW-\nThat Lambert (LAM) has\nalready covered its $8 dividend.\nThat American Radiator\n(ADT) will maintain its pre\nsent dividend rate.\nThat the textile industry\nhas taken a turn for the bet\nter and this Is regarded as en\ncouraging. In 1921 this in\ndustry\u2019s upturn preceded a\ngeneral betterment of condi\ntions.\nThat both Auto-Strop (AUZ)\nand Gillette (GIL) are attrac\ntive long pull purchases at\ntheir present prices.\nBacks Packers\nI\n\nA A\nIk Jh\n\u2014Time* Staff Photo\nALEXANDER LEGGE\nCHAIRMAN OF the Federal\nBoard, who yesterday said that\nthe board was in favor of modi\nfication of the famous packing\nconsent decree. Action is now\npending in the courts on the\nmodification plea.\nRimloLD\nDP MERGERS\nRailroad executives apparently\nhave entered into a tacit agree\nment not to put forward their\nrespective, merger plans until\nthe Seventy-first Congress ad\njourns on March 4, next, it was\nlearned today on high authority.\nAccording to this authority the\nresolution of Senator Couzens,\nRepublican of Michigan, propos\ning to forbid the approval of all\nrailroad consolidations and mer\ngers until the Interstate Com\nmission is given further powers\nby Congress is responsible for\nt\u2019-\u2019- action.\nUnlikely to Pass House\nWhile the Couzens* resolution,\nwhich passed the Senate and\nwill be before the \u2019ousc when\nthe short session opens in De\ncember. was aimed primarily at\nthe Great No-t\u2019 \u2014n-Northem Pa\ncific merger, it \u2019\u2019-d ths effect\nof causing half a dozen or more\nambitious merger plans to be\nwithdrawn from the Interstate\nCommerce\nThe re\u201d executi evi\ndently to the co -elusion\nthat the great amount of time\nrequired and the heavy cost in\nvolved in working out their vari\nous plans, would be vitiated by\nthe passage of t v Couzens\u2019 reso\nlution. As the* Northern merger\nb~- uo indefinitely\nthere is apparently ,no need for\nthis resolution and it is expected\nto fail passage.\nPlay for More Time\nThe new Congress might have\na different complexion, but be\nfore it comes into being there\nwill be ample time for the rail\nroads to work out their plans\nbefore further Interference can\narise.\nAnother re\u00b0 c on for the suspen\nsion of activity in this direction\nis the state of the stock market\nin which railroad securities and\nholding companies have suffer--\u2019\nDoes White House\nCarry a Curse?\nTragic Misfortune\nWhich Hovers\nAbout the\nWhite House\nA revelation of a rather\nstartling series of hap\npenings which have per\nsuaded many to believe\nthat the Presidential\nmansion carries a curse\nto those who live there!\nExclusively\nIn the\nAmerican\nWeekly\nSection of The\nI\nWASHINGTON HERALD\nTOMORROW\n3 FIRMS QUIT\nEXCHANGE;4\nTRANSFER\nt\nRetirement Is Indicated by Sale\nof Seats Belonging to Floor\nMembers; Brokaw Buys\nThe retirement of three firms\nfrom membership in the New\nstock Exchange was indl-\ncated today by the sale of the\nseats of their floor members.\nVan H. Cartmell, of Hale.\nWAters <fe Co., has sold his seat\nfor $251,000 to Milton Blauner,\nwho will become an individual\nfloor broker. Mr. Cartmell pur\nchased his seat earlier this year\nat a considerably higher price\nthan he obtained by its sale.\nSince this is the only seat Hale,\nWaters <fc Co. had on the Ex\nchange it indicates that the firm\nwill retire as a member. It wa4\nlearned, however, that the con\ncern, which was organized in\n1922, will remain as investment\nbankers, which they were before\nbecoming Stock Exchange mem\nbers.\nBrokaw Buys Seat\nClifford V. Brokaw, member of\nthe Four Hundred, has purchased\nthe New York Stock Exchange\nseat of Francis X. Deery for $262,-\n000, subject to approval by the\nmembership committee of the\nExchange. Deery bought his seat\non March 28, 1929, when seats\nwere selling above 1400.000. He\nhas been a partner in Watson\nWhite.\nBrokaw was graduated from the\nSheffield Scientific School of\nYale University in 1925. He was\nmarried to Audrey Stanson Joel\non September 1, 1927.\nGibb Pays $265,000\nThe partners of Gardner Co.,\nit was learned, have not yet de\ncided as to whether they will con\ntinue in business.\nStetson has just organized an\ninvestment firm in Philadelphia\nunder the name of Stetson\nBlackman, with offices in the\nPackard Building. Blackman was\nformerly associated with the\nbanking firm of Boening Co.\nThe sale of the seat of George\nA. Winsor, of Winsor, Trowbridge\nCo. to Robert A. Gibb, for $265,-\n000 will automatically retire the\nfirm since the seat sold is the only\none they had.\nWinsor bought his seat on April\n4, 1929. His firm was organized\nin 1923 as investment bankers. It\ncould not be learned whether they\nwill continue business.\nGardner Co. have also indi\ncated their retirement with the\nsale of the seat to Nathan\nMarkoe. their floor member, for\n$265,000 to John B. Stetson, jr.,\nformer United States minister to\nPoland, and son of the hat manu\nfacturer. He is 46 years old and\nis a graduate of Harvard, class of\n1906. In addition to being a dip\nlomat and a member of the Stock\nExchange, he has also translated\nseveral books on Brazil from the\nPortugese.\nWilliam H. Pflugfelder. of Theo\ndore Prince Co., has transferred\nhis membership to James E. Sau\nter of the same firm.\nThe transfer of the member\nship of Howes Burton, John J.\nGillooly, Walter J. Rich, jr., and\nJulian A. Morris to Robert L.\nHarding, Marcus S. Friendlander,\nHoward S. Filston and William\nRaebeck, respectively, has been\napproved by the New York Stock\nExchange.\nArrangements have been made\nfor the sale of a seat at $255,000,\nup $4,000 from the last previous\nsale, it was announced today.\n15","height":"30306","width":"24221"}}
